00:00:18.933 --> 00:00:25.332
in this video I am going to explain fourier series representation of continuous time periodic signals

00:00:26.448 --> 00:00:31.692
assume that we have a periodic complex exponential signal y of t

00:00:31.692 --> 00:00:37.356
this signal has harmonically related signals shown with phi sub k here

00:00:37.356 --> 00:00:44.417
each harmonically related signal has a fundamental frequency that is a multiple of omega zero

00:00:44.417 --> 00:00:50.520
a linear combination of harmonically related complex exponentials has the form given below

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:54.647
this signal is also periodic with a period of t

00:00:54.647 --> 00:00:59.032
here the term for k is equal to zero is constant

00:00:59.032 --> 00:01:08.392
and the terms for k is equal to plus one and k is equal to minus one are referred to as first harmonic components

00:01:08.392 --> 00:01:17.378
in a similar way when k equals minus two or plus two the components are called second harmonic components

00:01:18.868 --> 00:01:29.964
the representation of periodic signals as the linear combination of harmonically related complex exponentials is referred to as fourier series representation

00:01:29.964 --> 00:01:34.148
here two questions arise based on this representation

00:01:34.148 --> 00:01:38.677
first how can we determine the coefficients a sub k's

00:01:38.677 --> 00:01:43.669
second how broad class of signals can be represented in this way

00:01:45.590 --> 00:01:47.836
let's start with the first question

00:01:47.836 --> 00:01:53.264
fourier series coefficients are computed as given in the second equation

00:01:53.264 --> 00:01:55.732
which is called the synthesis equation

00:01:55.732 --> 00:02:00.792
note that fourier series representation is called the analysis equation

00:02:00.792 --> 00:02:07.540
