00:02:09.792 --> 00:02:17.530
so let's move to the second question which asks how broad class signals can be represented as fourier series

00:02:17.530 --> 00:02:23.943
the answer is that fourier series can be used to represent an extremely large class of signals

00:02:23.943 --> 00:02:32.620
in the next slides I am going to explain the conditions for the signals that guarantee the existence of fourier series representation

00:02:35.203 --> 00:02:44.773
let's first assume that we represent the signal x of t using finite series so that the summation is from minus n to plus n

00:02:44.773 --> 00:02:52.024
the error between the original signal and the finite series representation is called the approximation error

00:02:52.024 --> 00:03:02.542
if the signal x of t has a fourier series representation then the energy in the error over one period goes to zero when n goes to infinity

00:03:04.075 --> 00:03:12.349
one class of signals that have fourier series representation is the signals that have finite energy over one period

00:03:12.349 --> 00:03:15.890
in other words the signal is square integrable

00:03:15.890 --> 00:03:27.861
when this condition is satisfied we are guaranteed that the coefficients are finite and the energy in the error over one period goes to zero when n goes to infinity

00:03:27.861 --> 00:03:36.816
however this does not imply that x of t and its fourier series representation are equal at any value of t

00:03:38.678 --> 00:03:43.289
an alternative set of conditions is dirichlet conditions

00:03:43.289 --> 00:03:48.921
first condition states that x of t must be absolutely integrable

00:03:48.921 --> 00:03:57.910
second condition states that x of t has a finite number of maxima and minima in any finite interval of time

00:03:57.910 --> 00:04:07.658
and the third and the last condition states that there are only a finite number of discontinuities in any finite interval of time

00:04:07.658 --> 00:04:17.316
this set of conditions guarantees that x of t equals its fourier series representation except at discontinuities

